Trends in travel prices since 1989
Until 1989, there were only five state travel agencies approved by the then ČSSR: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
The travel agencies sold mostly travel to the socialist Eastern bloc countries, and in the West they were only allowed to select.
And so Czech tourists traveled to the Baltic Sea (in the German Democratic Republic - the GDR), to the Soviet Union (Sochi on the Crimea Peninsula on the Black Sea), to Bulgaria and Romania to the Black Sea and to Hungary to the Balaton.
A slight exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when Yugoslavia was also allowed to travel, Yugoslavia took a pro-western course and therefore travel to Yugoslavia was severely restricted.
A great paradox of those socialist times was that even citizens of the Eastern bloc (also the Czechoslovak) were not allowed to travel freely within the framework of the socialist countries.
For example, if a citizen of the ČSSR wanted to travel to Poland individually or even to the Soviet Union, then he needed a so-called invitation letter, otherwise individual travel was not possible.
The travel agencies also offered travel to the west at the time, but then you had to buy huge snakes or even stay in the sleeping bag in front of the travel agency, or at least have "good acquaintances" in the travel agency.
That was not the way things had been going for a long time.
The so-called currency pledge - the condition for an exit to the West - was granted only "politically reliable" people - the others were not allowed to travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely exchangeable currency, so it would have been impossible to raise the necessary financial resources (Western currency) for a trip to the West.
The vast majority of Czechs therefore spent their holidays in the country, no wonder that the Czechs bought countless weekend houses and dates - a habit that continues to this day.
The 1989 revolution followed a journey revolution of the Czechs on foot.
While a holiday in the GDR or in Bulgaria was the measure of all things until 1989, the Czechs spent 4.5 million of their holidays abroad in countries around the world last year.
A huge paradox, which one is not even aware of today, is the fact that one could not travel to the currently most popular holiday country of the Czech Republic - Croatia until 1989 at all because it was part of the Yugoslavia of that time.
Just from the beginning of the 90s of the last century, foreign exchange obligations were lifted in the neighbouring Western European countries, which led to a huge wave of short visits mainly to Vienna in Austria and to Germany.
The Czechoslovaks could for a long time get from their travels to the west simply not enough, everyone wanted to have been there at least a few days.
Thus, the Czech holidaymakers slept in the park when traveling to Paris in the tent, because who would have had the money for an accommodation in the hotel or in a pension at that time.
A typical feature of travel abroad from the Czech Republic was a packed trunk with canned, beer and permanent sausage etc.
Another important milestone was the introduction of the freely exchangeable Czech krone - after decades our tourists were finally able to buy the Western currency freely.
Our level of life and therefore the average salaries increased, which resulted in another important moment in 1997.
Thanks to the increased demand for travel, the travel agencies began to regularly prepare journeys through charter flights after 1997, making the journeys impossible thanks to the possibility of negotiating volume discounts compared to the past.
At the end of the 1990s, with the exception of the United States, the Czechs had already currencyless payments with all highly developed countries of the world, making travel even easier.
Another interesting moment in the history of "post-general" travel came in 2000, when thanks to the high demand of the first direct charter flight to an exotic country - to Thailand.
Every year, direct charter aircraft with Czech passengers have been flying in far-off sunny countries, and this year 12 exotic destinations are flown directly from the Czech Republic.
100 thousand Czechs travel to exotic countries every year!
Another important moment in the era that marked our "post-revolutionary" development came in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the US lifted the visa requirement for Czech tourists, which made our country definitely one of the most advanced countries in the world.
In 2008, for the first time, the Czechs spent more than half of their holiday abroad (50.3%) and for the first time in their history they spent more than CZK 15 per head for a single holiday stay, including the cost at the resort.
