Climate atrocities slowed the economy
In the first year in which Mario López Valdez is in government, in Sinaloa unemployment and undeclared work rose, while foreign investment went down and the economy stagnated.
2011 will be remembered in the economic history of Sinaloas. It is the first year in which Mario López Valdez, who described himself as the initiator of the change and made great hopes for economic growth, is in government. However, due to the climatic hardships, growth cannot be the talk but, on the contrary, the main economic indicators deteriorated.
The low temperatures in February caused not only losses in millions of jobs in agriculture but also limited the growth of the national economy and caused a general decline in economic activity by 3.6 percent in the first quarter, mainly due to the historical decline in agricultural development by 31.16 percent, which slowed down further sectors of the economy.
According to a report published by Consejo Mexicano para el Desarrollo Rural Sustentable (Mexican Council for Sustainable Agricultural Development) on the effects of the frost, 582,000 hectares of land used in agriculture were damaged, 78.03 percent of which were completely destroyed and the remaining 21.07 percent were partially.
The decline in economic activity until November has steadily increased in the Mexican state. The Instituto Nacional de Estadística y Geografía observed a rapid increase in unemployment in the first quarter, since from January to March, 55,053 people had no employment, corresponding to 4.53 percent of the working population. In the second quarter, the unemployment rate increased to 5.28 percent and from July to September to 6.19 percent, resulting in 74,000 unemployed in Sinaloa. That is 18,969 people more than in the first quarter.
Less liquidity
Unemployment in Sinaloa in the year dates back to several factors. The economic scientist Gerardo López Cervantes, Dean of the Faculty of Economics and Social Sciences of the University of Autónoma (UAS), commented, the policy of the public institutions indirectly explains the growing unemployment.
"What we are currently seeing is an increase in unemployment, which has to do with several factors. Among other things, with loss of liquidity on the market as a result of the cuts in the average by the legislation adopted to combat money laundering in Congress, because for those who are forbidden to raise dollars, it is not easy to let them work for themselves, invest them or use anything else," he said.
Migration stopped
López Cervantes pointed out that increasing unemployment is also a demographic factor.
"The number of people who leave the country looking for work abroad, especially in the United States, has fallen. This is due, on the one hand, to the problems of entry and, on the other hand, because it is difficult to find work there. These people stay here and look for work here which makes unemployment rise," he says.
Blacksmiths' wares
The analysis of the Sinaloa labour market is even more serious if the high proportion of undeclared work is taken into account, which, according to INEGI, comprises 60.38 percent of the country's employees who work without paying into the social security funds.
Unemployment and undeclared work are the lowest wages in the whole of Mexico, according to the statistics of the Instituto Mexicano del Seguro Social (Mexican Social Security Institute) and the Secretaryía del Trabajo y Previsión Social (government agency for employment and social care in Mexico).
The average monthly income of Sinaloa workers was 5352 pesos until September, which is much less than the general government average, which is 7375 pesos.
Reduction of the ADI
In addition to the decline in economic activity and growing unemployment, the biggest decline in foreign direct investment (ADI) in the last ten years is recorded in 2011. According to Secretariía de Economía (State Economic Authority), the ADI from January to June was 630 597 dollars, which corresponds to a drop of 87.74 percent compared to the 5 143 312 dollars in the same period last year.
The Secretaría de Desarrollo Económico del Gobierno (Government Authority for Economic Development) has a total investment of 17 280 000 pesos in 2011, mainly from Tertiary companies.
The debts
In view of the economic crisis, in July at the National Congress, the government requested a loan of 3 000 000 000 pesos to be invested in reactivation of the economy in infrastructure projects in the 18 municipalities.
Reactions
For the representatives of entrepreneurship, the first year of government made Mario López Valdé's inability to rule clearly.
Miguel Loredo López, Chairman of the Cámara Nacional de la Industria de la Transformación (Maats Chamber of Manufacturing in Mexico) stated that in 2011 no efforts were made to harmonise the views of the different sectors, including the government of Mexico.
"The economic activity in Sinaloa was really very poor this year. It must be worked hard to regain the terrain lost this year and we need to make double efforts in 2012. The efforts of all and in particular the progress of the well-coordinated government team have not been sufficiently coordinated," he said.
Slow economic development
Loredo López said that events such as the frost at the beginning of the year made economic development of the country difficult and slowed down.
"The low economic flow is the result of several events, including the frost. One of the most important impacts is a slow economy, which is not sufficiently in motion to produce an economic dynamic that could produce an acceptable flow of processes, products and services. Therefore, we will conclude the year far below our expectations," he said.
Redefine vocation
Teodoro Salazar Uriarte, chairman of the Confederación Patronal de la República Mexicana ( Mexico Business Association) in Sinaloa, said that it was necessary to move the State to more dynamic productive activities.
"In general, we have observed that work has been done. We believe it is necessary to develop a long-term programme to redefine the economic vocation and line of the country, because it is important to activate all material and human resources Sinaloas," he said.
There's a lot to do
The Chairman of Coparmex stressed the importance of developing a future perspective that would lead the government's efforts to improve.
"In general, I would say that the government has achieved good results in various areas. Economic development has progressed, but it is important to develop a long-term programme," he said.
He stressed that the current state power had made progress with the government.
"There are areas in which one can say that the government has acted more comprehensively. What I can say is that work has been done and that the government is aware that a lot of work is ahead of it," he said.
