Conversion of analogues to digital signals has been one of the most important changes in the world over the last few years.
The Supreme Court of Mexico (SCJN) dismissed the constitutional complaints filed by the Senate and the House of Deputies against the presidential decree and called for the transfer of analogues to digital signals from 2021 to 2015, due to the lack of eight votes required to challenge the law.
A minority of four ministers, including the President of the Supreme Court, Juan Silva Meza, felt that President Felipe Calderón had not exceeded his responsibilities when he issued the Decree-Law with details on the switchover to terrestrial digital television.
This decision rejected the constitutional dispute raised by the Senate, since it did not receive the required qualified majority of eight votes, so that the court could decide on constitutionality or non-constitutionality. Thus, the law remains in force.
The project for the complaint, which was drafted by Minister Olga Sánchez Cordero, proposed to declare the Decree-Law unconstitutional, since the Comisión Federal de Telecomunicaciones (Cofetel) (Federal Commission for Telecommunications in Mexico) was responsible for the regulation of radio and television, which would contradict hierarchical principles and legal reservation.
Only Zaldívar, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margarita Luna and Sánchez Cordero voted in favour of the project.
With this argument, both the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies submitted constitutional complaints against the Decree-Law. Following the adoption of the lawsuits, Minister Sánchez Cordero no longer applied the Decree-Law and applied all activities to set up digital transmission.
The Council of Ministers also rejected the appeal filed by the Chamber of Deputies without entering the debate on the project for which Minister Sánchez Cordero was also responsible.
In its contribution, the Prime Minister stated that he did not agree to the arguments of the project, in the sense that the country government should not regulate the measures to be taken by the public administration by means of general rules.
"I also do not believe that if you do so, the independence of the regulatory body would be impaired." She also recalled that the central government is responsible for the planning of strategic policy areas, such as the telecommunications sector, for constitutional reasons, as it directs state affairs.
The replacement of analogue signals by digital is one of the most important changes that have taken place in recent years around the world, and it results in a better use of the radioelectric spectrum, an increased quality of the signal and more channels.
The postponement of the changeover, she said, was a postponement of the exploitation of digitalisation, which was a decision in the public interest, which had not only technical aspects, "because it covered economic, social, political and security aspects."
These matters, she stressed, "needed to act on the whole system, in accordance with the principle of economic governance by the state, they included a group of features that put the Constitution in the hands of the central government."
It called to mind that many countries around the world had already carried out the digital transformation, even though they had highly specialised facilities.
It was not possible to conclude that the government intervened in the powers of the Congress with the publication of the contested decree, because the laws adopted by the legislature would be complied with," she assured.
