In this sense, the President of the Consejo General del Instituto Elekctoral de Michoacán (IEM), María de los Ángeles Llanderal Zaragoza, recalled that only last 9 November the electoral office had adopted a number of regulations on the harmonisation of local rules with the reforms of the states in electoral matters.
It should be recalled that Michoacán had neither adapted his political constitution nor his electoral law nor his law on electoral justice to the reforms adopted by the Congress, so that they did not enter into force at this round of elections. Governor Leonel Godoy Rangel avoided their publication in the Public Prosecutor within the time limits provided for by the argument or objections.
On 9 November, the Supreme Court of Mexico (SCJN) decided on the constitutional appeal filed by the local legislature and judged the Ombudsman's vote on the constitutional reforms as "invalid and illegal" since it did not have the right to "determine or veto".
María de los Ángeles Llanderal explained in an interview about the possibility of individual counting of votes that, thanks to the adoption of the guidelines by the Consejo General del IEM, the possibility would now be that the local electoral authority could count the ballots in part or in full.
Under the following conditions, the votes contained in one or more ballots may be partially counted The results of the protocols do not match; the record of the counting and calculation of votes is not available or is not owned by the Chairman of the Election Committee or there are obvious errors or amendments in the protocols.
In addition, if there is a difference between the likely winner and the one on second place, which is equal to or less than one percent, the total number of all ballots may be distributed, provided that at the beginning of the meeting there is an explicit request from the party or coalition chairman, who is the second of the candidates mentioned.
Voting may also take place in their entirety if, after completion of the ordinary calculation, it is established that the difference between the likely winner and the candidate in the second place is equal to or less than one percent, provided that there is an explicit request from a representative of the party whose candidate has become second. In this case, the election packages that have been partially counted would be excluded.
