The zähelastic behaviour of the asphalt means that it behaves like a liquid at high temperatures of almost 180°C, at 120°C it is very viscous and almost solid at 50°C, while it breaks at very low temperatures.
"This means that the resistance of asphalt on the roads is not uniform, but changes in one day depending on the weather conditions and temperature fluctuations," explained the chemical engineer.
The researcher of the FQ noted that the streets of Mexico City had a majority of a flexible pavement composed of six layers of material, the last three of which included asphalt.
Between the top layers lies a wear layer of asphalt, made of small asphalt and then fortified stones.
Each stone of this wear layer was bathed in asphalt.
When the vehicles continue to move and generate forces on it, this layer enables a good distribution of forces in the road surface.
"If it were modified asphalt, the forces would be even better distributed," said the chemical engineer.
"Over the wear layer," he explained, "a final layer will be laid out, the so-called bearing layer consisting of tiny stones, i.e., sand bathed in asphalt as well.
Since this layer is in contact with the vehicle tyres, it needs a greater mechanical force than the wear layer and it needs to produce friction.
The most powerful and distributed of this pavement also needs a proper thickness and the material from which it is made must be maintained.
The weather conditions, especially humidity and temperature fluctuations, are other important factors to consider, above all the water," he said, "because it significantly affects the behaviour of the wear layer.
When the terrain gets wet, water penetrates the layer and only comes out difficult again. This causes a softening of all layers of the pavement and, as a result, the appearance of potholes.
When a punch hole occurs," he said, "the cover layer will be removed first, while the wear layer will only be affected afterwards. But the damage does not occur immediately, but it is a process that would have to be maintained during the first signs by adequate maintenance programs."
The member of the Sistema Nacional de Investigadores (National Research System of Mexico) stated that the vehicle load was another important cause of the occurrence of impact holes. Therefore, the thickness of each layer of the road surface always had to be proportionate to the vehicle load and it had to be ensured that this regulation was complied with in order to avoid frequent impact holes.
