Entry of a "golden budget rule" into the Constitution
On Tuesday, the Government of the Great Social-Democratic Coalition, which is in power in Austria, decided to include a "Golden Budget Rule" in the Constitution to reduce public deficits and also to avoid possible degradation by rating agencies in the Austrian top-bonality (AAA).
It was the social-democratic chancellor Werner Faymann who personally announced this decision on the outcome of the Council of Ministers, although the Austrian public debt is 74.6%, far above the 60% criterion laid down by the Maastricht Treaty, but clearly below the debt levels of the countries such as Italy, Greece or Spain.
"If Austria's ability to pay was not reduced to a blow from AAA to AA+, we would have to pay three billion euros of interest each year," argued Michael Spindelegger, Vice Chancellor and Christian Democratic Auβenminister.
Austria also issued a call for the Brussels Eurozone Member State Summit of 26 October: The Heads of State and Government would then have demanded the inclusion of the reduction of public deficits by the end of 2012 and a return to the balance of public accounts in the Constitution or the adoption of an equivalent law.
The measure taken by the Austrian Government is similar to the "German model" since Germany was the first European country to have incorporated such a "rule" into the Constitution.
By 2017, the structural budget deficit should decrease by 0.75% of gross domestic product (GDP) each year, while the government's structural budget deficit should not exceed 0.35% of GDP from 2017 onwards, whereas regional states should have balanced households as well as municipalities.
The aim is to eliminate budgetary debt under the 60% criterion set by the Maastricht Agreement in the 2020/21 horizon.
