Energy policy:
Facts should prevail over dogmas
If a topic does not exist on the basis of short-term considerations or emotions, this is certainly the energy policy.
The availability and cost of electricity directly influence the purchasing power and the competitiveness of the companies.
It is reasonable to set up an electoral meeting to reflect on this issue and on the position of nuclear energy.
The debate will only bear fruit if it explores the overall economic, social and environmental consequences of the proposed options.
The French should base their opinion on objective facts, rational data.
Although 7 billion people are on this planet, demographic evolution is leading to a doubling of electricity demand by 2050, it is not intended to avoid a huge proportion of the world's population on a vital element.
At the same time, it is necessary to mitigate the shortage of fossil resources in order to continue to be able to produce electricity without the imperative need to reduce greenhouse gas emissions, to forget an issue that has disappeared from the ecological debate in order to combat climatic irregularities.
The Fukushima accident doesn't change any of these parameters.
For this reason, Germany remains isolated in its decision to refrain from nuclear power.
This is not the case in Belgium, which is subject to its decision on the need to find a substitute source of substitution, nor in Switzerland, which only intends to build nuclear power plants of the last generation.
On the other hand, Great Britain, Finland, Poland, the Czech Republic, the Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India and Brazil, to name just a few countries, continue to pursue their projects with determination.
After Fukushima, the United States decided to attract another unit to its park by re-establishing the plant Three Mile Island, which was shut down after the nuclear accident.
Although the German model, which is sometimes focused on renewable energy sources, is sometimes set as a model, reality contradicts the discourse.
The elections in Berlin will take the form of an increase in the price of electricity, an increase in energy dependence, in particular on Russia, by the increased use of imported gas, an increase in CO2 emissions caused by gas and coal-fired power plants.
The totality of these unpleasant effects will already become evident within a few months.
The case of Denmark gives rise to reflection.
Denmark, on the one hand, is a European leader in wind energy from which it refers to 30% of its electricity, on the other hand, the country is one of the strongest users of coal and gas, alternately used with wind energy; on the other hand, its CO2 emissions and its electricity price are respectively 65% and 50% higher than the European average.
Thanks to the stability of our energy policy, our neighbours pay a 40% higher electricity bill in contrast to our French households.
As the energy price in the globalised economy represents a key role of competitiveness and a stability path for industry on national soil, French companies have an advantage due to the most favourable electricity in Europe.
Any significant reduction in nuclear power would therefore result in a strong increase in the price of energy, which will lead to the noble statements about the reindustrialisation of our country and the defence of purchasing power.
Surveys showed that this is a price that the vast majority of French people are as unwilling to pay as it shows resistance to the principle of this source of energy.
Let us note that the energy policy of our country has enabled us to build an industrial sector with 125.00 direct jobs and 410,000 jobs induced.
Because of its strong export character, it brings a large number of specialized small and medium-sized enterprises to international markets and makes them the creators of countless jobs.
If France were to take the decision to increase nuclear power, the majority of these SMEs would be the victims, and the annual EUR 6 billion of investment goods and nuclear exports would be increasingly shrinking.
What electrician would commission an EPR designed to function for sixty years if the decline of his producer was pre-programmed?
In order to solve the energetic equation, one has to admit that as little as a devil's work there is a miracle means of generating electricity.
The low-carbon solutions developed by the Areva company for the use of nuclear power and renewable energy testify to the complementarity of energy sources.
Maintaining the highest possible level of safety is an absolute imperative for nuclear power.
In France, we have a security authority that conducts uncompromising and transparent controls in existing works, such as building in Flamanville.
Their work teams, who have made a name for themselves because of their professionalism, are currently obsessed with the security concept.
Within 50 years, the nuclear industry has experienced three serious accidents.
Only a single one, in Three Mile Island, has entered the market under normal operating conditions, thus without any consequences for man and the environment.
In Chernobyl, the drama was challenged by reactor construction as well as inexcusable human failure.
At Fukushima some seem to forget that the accident of two natural disasters has never been caused by the presence of a mass that caused the death of several tens of thousands of people.
The nuclear industry will draw its lessons from this accident as it did after the two previous ones.
As a fruit of this approach, as well as a cooperation between the safety authorities of the French and German operators and constructors of nuclear power plants, the EPR constitutes a draft that enables them to withstand such phenomena.
Since it is considered desirable among the electrical engineers to build a nuclear power plant, a construction stop in Flamanville would be a fabulous gift to the competition between Areva and EDF by allowing them free train to travel the leading position in the inevitable nuclear power development.
It is essential and legitimate to look for the best energy bouquet for our country, but it would be irresponsible to let emotions, dogmas and party manoeuvring dominate a debate that also determines the economic, social and financial situation of our country.
Is immigration a burden or a chance for the economy?
The immigration policy under Nicolas Sarkozy has been criticised from many angles - the overburden of police, judicial and administrative bodies on the basis of a policy subject to the figures, the compatibility of this policy with the status of a "country of human rights", as France had called itself.
Recently, the public harassment against foreign students had marked the weekly shows, the Minister of the Interior had casually announced (see Libération of 23 May) that France "needed no talents, maurers or waitress from abroad".
But this policy was rarely analysed from an economic point of view.
There is a broad consensus on this issue between the right and the left.
On the right was Jacques Chirac's tone, who declared in 1976 that "900,000 unemployed, including over 2 million immigrant workers, would not represent a problem for a country" on the left by Michel Rocard, who had explained in 1990 that France "could not absorb the whole poverty of the world".
There is only one difference in the degree of gravity.
The fear of the invasion of the national soil by Horden Polish plumber was shared both from the right and from the left in 2005.
From both camps the immigrants were perceived as a burden for the economy and the French society.
The only difference is the degree of generosity that immigrants are willing to accept.
In his programme, Francois Hollande is limited to banalities, which indicate that partnership development allows us to solve our "migration problems".
This idea of immigration as a burden, as a problem, may have an impact on the elections, but it is economically costly.
As Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron showed us in a recent work that summarizes the latest findings on immigration (Exceptional People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Define Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 S.), there is a broad consensus among specialists regarding the positive influence of the influx of immigrants on economic growth, wages and jobs in the countries of immigration.
Reducing immigration would reduce growth and damage the labour market situation.
The fears about the influence of migrants are based on the idea that they threaten to substitute the local workers, especially the less qualified, by exerting pressure on their wages.
Experience shows, however, that immigrants are, in fact, much more complementary than local wage earners, since they are mainly engaged in occupations in sectors that are technically unburdened.
The low-skilled immigrants work in sectors where local wage-earners are not interested, which are more skilled among immigrants working in dynamic sectors where training is not aligned with the labour supply.
Positive wage effect
Just as a surgeon would have difficulty working in a country where there is a shortage of anesthesiologists, so this complementarity also has a positive effect on the labour market situation between locals and migrants.
Giovanni Peri has calculated in this way that a 1% increase in the influx of immigrants causes a co-related, long-term increase in real wages between 0.6% and 0.9%.
And this without account being taken of the fact that the diversity of ideas brought in by immigrants and economic growth is beneficial (high share of immigrant immigrants among American Nobel Laureates; Google, Intel, Paypal, eBay and Yahoo were founded by immigrants).
Migrants also contribute net to the social systems in the European countries, on average about 1% of the total budget.
The World Labour Organisation estimates, for example, that a person who migrates to Germany at the age of 30 makes an average net contribution (income minus expenditure) of around EUR 150,000 to the public budget over his lifetime.
Nicolas Sarkozy wished to bring the missing cutting points with the teeth at the time of his mandate.
These said teeth, which the immigrants were supposed to deter, however, achieved exactly the opposite effect.
