Nord Stream, new gateway to Russian gas in Europe
The North Stream gas pipeline, which runs on the Baltic seabed and connects Western Europe directly with Russia, has been put into operation.
It is intended to supply gas for an equivalent of 30 million households.
The Russian gas giant Gazprom wanted to perform this event with brilliance and Gloria.
Over 500 invited guests, including four heads of state and government, have attended the opening of the new North Stream gas pipeline, which connects Russia and Germany directly to the sea level on the Baltic Sea coast during the last Tuesday under orchestral sound and at fine taste buffet.
The German chancellor Angelika Merkel, Russian President Dmitri Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his colleague Mark Rutte from the Netherlands have symbolically combined the valve's load, which carries the Russian gas into the Western European network.
With the new gas pipeline, 27.5 billion cubic metres of additional Russian gas per year will be delivered to Western Europe through a first 1224 km long pipeline linking the region of Saint Petersburg with Mecklenburg-Vorpommern.
A second pipeline, which allows a total supply of 55 billion cubic metres of gas - the equivalent of total French consumption - is due to be completed by the end of 2012.
And you already let the possibility of building a third line on your own track begin.
For Gazprom, the timely and precise completion of this huge building seems like a victory.
The project was highly controversial in Poland and the Baltic States.
The Nord-Stream pipeline will allow direct gas delivery to Germany, while avoiding any route through third countries (Poland or Ukraine) on the land roads.
For this reason, these two countries lose a little of their power: it is now more difficult for them to exert pressure on Russia by threatening to close access to Western European markets.
Warsaw, the strongest in the debate, was not shy away from comparing the North Stream pipeline with a "new German-Swiss Pact" in connection with the alliance between Hitler and Stalin for the occupation of Poland in 1939.
This means that the issue is politically more sensitive.
Western Europe has gained even greater security of supply through the support of this Russian project.
This, however, is at the expense of a deforestation of European energy, as the project has struck a break between Western and Eastern Europeans.
Russia has managed to achieve its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich, Western countries, which have strong gas consumption and whose gas reserves are going to decline.
"This gas pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, it is a new artery that connects us in an organic way," said François Fillon at the inauguration of the gas pipeline, pointing to the degree to which the large gas contracts are also important from a political and economic point of view.
All this explains the broad smile of the numerous Gazprom Managers represented in Lubmin regarding the gas supply.
The construction of this gas pipeline is also an outstanding technique.
The underwater pipe is made of steel with concrete lining to protect it from anchors.
It rests on the seabed, at about 200 m deep.
During her construction, minefields dating from World War II had to be balanced.
"A hundred or so mines had to be removed or destroyed cautiously," said Jens Müller, spokesman for Nord Stream.
In addition, increased measures had to be taken to protect fauna and flora.
The line is a long hose made of metal, heavy like 242 Eiffel Towers, which is interrupted by nothing over the entire length: neither by valves, nor by maintenance stations.
A control platform was planned off Sweden's coast, but project managers have taken a step away, as Sweden was not keen to see a Russian state company settle on its shores in a permanent manner.
"In the case of a disaster, we close the gas passage in less than a minute," Jens Müller explained.
In the event of a leak, the gas in the gas pipeline thus escapes into the air.
However, this case is considered unlikely by the constructors, since the tails were estimated to have a leak resistance per 100,000 years.
The state monitoring of the gas pipeline is ensured by both an underwater robot controlled by a seaship for external surveillance purposes and by an apparatus circulating within the gas pipeline.
It has the shape of a cigar, measuring one metre in diameter, is introduced into the inside of the pipe and is moved by the gas pressure.
After three full days of the line movement at a speed of 3 meters per second, the device provides the most accurate information about any deformations of the metal upon arrival.
The gas pipeline was designed to work for fifty years without even having to undergo the least repair.
The gas circulation is easily ensured by pressure.
This is 200 bar at the entrance, 100 bar at the exit point.
Five societies have united their forces to achieve this project.
However, the management remains in the hands of Gazprom, which holds 51% of the shares.
In addition, the German companies E.ON and BASF (each 15,5%), as well as the Dutch gas union and the French group GDF Suez (one to 9%) are affiliated here.
These five companies have formed a business community called Nord Stream, which is responsible for the construction and operation of the gas pipeline.
It is based in Zug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Gazprom has thus rented the entire capacity of its gas transport to the renewable 20th-year contract.
"Gazprom will pay for the total capacity, no matter how large the real transporter gas volume fails," Jens Müller explained.
The financing of gas pipeline construction was secured to 30% of shareholders and to 70% by bank loans.
Total labour costs should be EUR 7.4 billion for both pipelines.
For example, for GDF Suez, the investment amount was 240 million.
However, minority shareholders are committed to recovering their expenses, as Gazprom alone bears the liability risk.
The gas pipeline enters a sandy coastal line with pine wooded pines at Lubmin from the Baltic Sea.
The 4.5-metre-high valves form the gas outlet pumps.
Sensors measure pressure, temperature and other key figures of the incoming gas before it is transmitted to the German gas pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, this terminal has been supplied with a million cubic metres of Russian gas per hour.
With full capacity, this would be 3 million cubic metres per hour and 6 million in 2012.
